		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Metamodelling for Grammarware Researchers</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/RichardFPaige.html">Richard F. Paige</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/FionaPolack.html">Fiona Polack</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_5">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_5</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2012s/paper01.html"><em>A tutorial on metamodelling for grammar researchers</em></a> (SLE 2012 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagM">T6D: Synergies</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s explicit goal is to bridge “grammarware” and “modelware” communities by aligning concepts and practices.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It reframes grammar-based language engineering artifacts in terms of meta-modeling concepts and notations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It discusses tool-supported workflows (e.g., with EMF-style meta-models) that grammarware researchers can adopt.
</li></ul></li></ul>
